Notes: 

A good rule:
Instructions file = always-needed repo behavior
Skill / prompt file = task-specific guidance
Prompt = current problem only


Here are clean speaker bullet points you can use in your presentation on GitHub Copilot instructions:

## Talk track bullets

 GitHub Copilot instructions help guide Copilot’s behavior for our project
 They act like team-level guidance, not a one-time prompt
 We use them to make Copilot generate code closer to our coding standards
 This is useful for consistency across developers, services, and repositories

## What instructions do

 They provide project context automatically
 They tell Copilot how our team prefers code to be written
 They reduce the need to repeat the same guidance in every prompt
 They help Copilot follow architecture and engineering patterns already used in the repo

## Simple real-world example

 In a Spring Boot project, we can instruct Copilot to use constructor injection
 We can ask it to follow layered architecture: controller, service, repository
 We can tell it to use JUnit 5 and Mockito for tests
 We can remind it not to log secrets, tokens, or PII
 This makes generated code more enterprise-ready from the start

## Why teams use instructions

 Improves consistency
 Reduces repetitive prompting
 Helps new developers get aligned faster
 Makes Copilot outputs closer to team expectations
 Supports governance and safer AI-assisted development

## Important point about tokens / context

 Yes, instructions consume context because Copilot has to read them
 That means very large instruction files can reduce room for task-specific context
 So the goal is not “more instructions,” but “better instructions”
 Keep them short, clear, stable, and high value

## Negative impacts if instructions are bad

 Too many instructions can make responses generic or rigid
 Outdated instructions can make Copilot suggest old patterns
 Conflicting instructions can confuse output quality
 Large instruction files can create unnecessary prompt overhead
 Poor instructions can hurt instead of help

## Best practice message

 Use instructions for always-true project guidance
 Do not use them for temporary tasks or sprint-specific notes
 Keep them focused on standards, architecture, testing, security, and validation
 Review them regularly as the codebase evolves

## Good content to place in instructions

 Java and Spring Boot version
 Testing framework and standards
 Dependency injection style
 API and validation conventions
 Exception handling pattern
 Logging and security rules
 Build and test commands

## What not to put in instructions

 Long architecture documents
 Temporary feature requirements
 Huge lists of generic coding rules
 Information developers already provide in the current prompt
 Anything stale, duplicated, or low value

## Strong one-line summary for speaking

 GitHub Copilot instructions are best when they are small, specific, and always relevant to the repository

## Closing line for presentation

 Think of instructions as the project’s default engineering guidance for Copilot: not too much, not too little, just enough to keep AI output aligned with the team

